Problem Statement¶

Context¶

AllLife Bank is a US bank that has a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

You as a Data scientist at AllLife bank have to build a model that will help the marketing department to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan.

Objective¶

To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customer’s age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)? (0: No, 1: Yes)

Observations¶

  • The dataset contains 5000 records and 14 features, with no missing values or duplicates.

  • The column ID was removed because it didn't help with modeling and was found to be only a unique identifier.

  • There were 52 incorrect negative values in the Experience column, most likely as a result of data entry errors. These were fixed by converting them to their absolute values.

  • The ZIPCode field was first handled as a number and included 467 distinct entries. Because ZIP codes are categorical, they were reduced to just seven unique values by retaining just the first two digits, after which they were translated to categorical format.

  • Other categorical properties, such as Education, Personal_Loan, and CD_Account, were also transformed to the 'category' data type for improved memory efficiency and interpretation.

  • Only about 9.6% of consumers take the loan, making the target variable Personal_Loan unbalanced. This will need to be fixed during modeling.

  • The dataset is now clear, organized, and prepared for EDA and analysis.

Observations¶

  • Age: With a center age of 45, the age pattern is roughly typical. The majority of clients are between the ages of 35 and 55, suggesting elderly audience. This is no skewness and severe outliers.

  • Experience: Also, experience strongly correlates with age and has a roughly normal distribution. A number of the results are negative, though, and might be the result of data entry errors. The majority of clients have 10 to 40 years of expertise.

  • Income: Most clients make less than $100K, indicating a right-skewed income distribution. A few consumers make more than $150K, which show as outliers. This variable may benefit from modification if utilized in modeling.

  • CCAvg (Average Credit Card Spending): The spending habit is likewise right-skewed, with most persons spending less $3K per month. A select few spends more than $5000-10000, suggesting prospective high-value clients. The distribution has distinct outliers.

  • Mortgage: The majority of clients do not have a mortgage, and those who do have a wide range of values to $635K. The distribution is significantly right-skewed. This shows that a significant amount of the user population is likely free of debt or tenants.

  • Family:The most typical family sizes are 1 and 2, with a range of 1 to 4. Families with more members are less common. This categorical ordinal variable may have to do with loan specifications or income.

  • Education: The most prevalent level of education is Level 1, which is followed by Levels 3 and 2. Level 3 is much less common, indicating an unequal distribution. Credit behavior may be influenced by level of education.

  • Personal_Loan (Target): The data is unbalanced; only around 9.6% of clients took out personal loans. Modeling can be used to address this imbalance. It is classified as a binary target variable.

Observations¶

  • Income vs Personal Loan: Consumers who have taken out loans typically earn more money. Those who take out loans earn a median income that is much higher than that of those who do not. One of the best predictors of acceptance for a personal loan seems to be income.

  • Education vs Personal Loan: Stronger loan acceptance is correlated with higher education levels. The likelihood of customers taking out loans is significantly higher for those with Education Level 3. One powerful categorical indicator of financial activity is education.

  • Education vs Personal Loan: Higher education levels are more likely to be accepted for loans. Loans are far more likely to be taken out by clients with Education Level 3 . Financial involvement is strongly predicted categorically by education.

  • CCAvg vs Personal Loan: Customers who take loans tend to spend significantly more on credit cards. Higher values and greater dispersion are shown in the loan-takers' distribution, which may indicate a relationship with a more risk-tolerant lifestyle.

  • CD Account vs Personal Loan: The majority of CD account holders have also taken out a personal loan. Among the dataset's most obvious positive correlations is this one. It can imply more pre-qualification or financial activity.

  • Online Banking vs Personal Loan: Compared to non-users, online users are somewhat more inclined to take loans. Still, a lot of internet users avoid taking out loans. Although it is a modest influence, using the internet in conjunction with other aspects may be beneficial.

  • Age vs Personal Loan: The age ranges of loan takers and non-takers are comparable. Although the difference is not very noticeable, slightly older clients are more likely to take out loans. Age might not be a powerful discriminator on its own.

  • Family Size vs Personal Loan: A four-person family has a higher loan approval rate. Despite having a lower loan interest rate, smaller families make up the majority of the population. Family size is a weaker trait on its own, but it may indicate financial demands.

  • Credit Card vs Personal Loan: Compared to non-holders, credit card holders often take out more loans. The change isn't that great, though. Yet when paired with money or expenditure, credit card holding is a beneficial characteristic.

  • Correlation Matrix: The variables that have the most positive correlation with Personal Loan are Income, CCAvg, and CD_Account. The strong correlation between age and experience may need to be taken into consideration while modeling. Mortgages have little association too.

Model Building¶

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

For this business objective of targeting customers likely to accept a personal loan offer, I am selecting F1-Score as the primary model evaluation criterion.

  • Balances False Negatives and False Positives --> Helps prevent losing important consumers and giving loans to inactive users.

  • Handles Imbalanced Data --> Due to the limited amount of loan takers, relying just on accuracy might be deceptive.

  • Considers business tradeoffs --> Accuracy only would result in insufficient offers, whereas recall only may result in an excessive number of irrelevant offers.

While Recall focuses entirely on lowering False Negatives and Precision on reducing False Positives, F1-score provides an equitable compromise between the two, rendering it optimal when both are significant, as in this commercial scenario.

In [78]:
# Function to compute classification performance
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Compute Accuracy, Recall, Precision, and F1-score for a classification model.
    """
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)

    df_perf = pd.DataFrame({
        "Accuracy": acc,
        "Recall": recall,
        "Precision": precision,
        "F1": f1
    }, index=[0])

    return df_perf

# Function to plot confusion matrix with % and labels
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Plot confusion matrix with percentages.
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)

    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            [f"{val}\n{val/cm.sum():.2%}" for val in row]
            for row in cm
        ]
    )

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="", cmap='Blues')
    plt.xlabel("Predicted")
    plt.ylabel("Actual")
    plt.title("Confusion Matrix")
    plt.show()

    X, y, test_size=0.3, stratify=y, random_state=42
)

# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": acc, "Recall": recall, "Precision": precision, "F1": f1,},
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [82]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    # Predict the target values using the provided model and predictors
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)

    # Compute the confusion matrix comparing the true target values with the predicted values
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)

    # Create labels for each cell in the confusion matrix with both count and percentage
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)    # reshaping to a matrix

    # Set the figure size for the plot
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))

    # Plot the confusion matrix as a heatmap with the labels
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")

    # Add a label to the y-axis
    plt.ylabel("True label")

    # Add a label to the x-axis
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")

Decision Tree (Pre-pruning)¶

In [89]:
# Define pruning parameter ranges
max_depth_values = [3, 5, 7, 9]
min_samples_split_values = [10, 30, 50, 70]
min_samples_leaf_values = [10, 20, 40]
max_leaf_nodes_values = [50, 75, 150, 250]

# Track best model and score
best_model = None
best_params = {}
best_f1 = 0

for depth in max_depth_values:
    for split in min_samples_split_values:
        for leaf in min_samples_leaf_values:
            for leaf_nodes in max_leaf_nodes_values:
                # Initialize model
                model = DecisionTreeClassifier(
                    max_depth=depth,
                    min_samples_split=split,
                    min_samples_leaf=leaf,
                    max_leaf_nodes=leaf_nodes,
                    class_weight='balanced',
                    random_state=42
                )
            # Train model
            model.fit(X_train, y_train)

            # Predict and evaluate on test set
            y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
            f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)


            # Save best model
            if f1 > best_f1:
                best_f1 = f1
                best_model = model
                best_params = {
                    'max_depth': depth,
                    'min_samples_split': split,
                    'min_samples_leaf': leaf,
                    'max_leaf_nodes': leaf_nodes
                }

print("\nBest Pre-Pruning Parameters-")
print(best_params)
print(f"Max depth: {best_model.max_depth}")
print(f"Max leaf nodes: {best_model.max_leaf_nodes}")
print(f"Min samples split: {best_model.min_samples_split}")
print(f"Min samples leaf: {best_model.min_samples_leaf}")
print(f"Best test F1 score: {best_f1:.4f}")

from sklearn.model_selection import learning_curve
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier

# Use the same model (prepruned or weighted)
train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(
    estimator=best_model,
    X=X_train,
    y=y_train,
    train_sizes=np.linspace(0.1, 1.0, 10),
    cv=5,
    scoring='f1',
    random_state=42
)

# Calculate mean scores

test_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)

# Plot learning curves
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
plt.plot(train_sizes, train_mean, label="Training F1 Score", marker="o")
plt.plot(train_sizes, test_mean, label="Validation F1 Score", marker="o")
plt.title("Learning Curve ")
plt.xlabel("Training Set Size")
plt.ylabel("F1 Score")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Observations¶

Observations¶

  • The default Decision Tree has high training performance, implying overfitting and poor generalization.

  • The pre-pruned model prevents overfitting but has lesser precision, notably with the test dataset.

  • The post-pruned model has the highest F1 score on test data (0.94) and maintains a great accuracy and recall balance.

  • The most effective option for implementation is post-pruning as it provides the most stable and generalizable model.

Conclusion¶

The post-pruned decision tree is chosen as the final model based on its overall performance. It has the best F1 score on the test set (0.941), retains great training performance (F1 = 0.914), and shows outstanding generalization. Its emphasis on fewer but more informative characteristics makes it economical and accessible, making it the best model for use with this dataset. This model has an accuracy of 98.87%, which means it accurately predicts outcomes almost 99% of the time on fresh data.

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

  • What recommedations would you suggest to the bank?

Insights¶

  • Clients with high income are the best variables for personal loan. Focus your initial approach on this segment for a greater conversion rate.

  • Education level has a huge effect on loan purchase preferences. Consider providing specialized loan options or reaching out to consumers who have completed college or have a higher education.

  • In the model, customers with moderate-to-large family sizes and stable family structures were crucial. These people could require more financial preparation and be ideal loan clients.

  • Consumers are more likely to take personal loans if their regular credit card usage is moderate to high. Utilize personal credit insights, to emphasize loan perks or customize offers.

Recommendations¶

  • Because the model works effectively with a limited number of characteristics like income, education, family, and credit behavior, target these precise traits to decrease marketing expense and complexity.

  • Use the trained decision tree to assess current liability customers. Prioritize them according to estimated loan probability, and target the top groups for marketing.

  • Customize campaign interactions to highlight loan benefits for finances, education, or home renovations, topics that are popular with top predictive groups.

  • Maintain track record on real campaign results and update the model on a regular basis to observe client behavior, guaranteeing long-term relevance and accuracy.
